<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><listPerson xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><person xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="BLO01" sex="1"><persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><roleName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/><forename xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Robert</forename><surname xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Bloomfield</surname><addName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/></persName><birth xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1766-12-03"><placeName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/></birth><death xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1823-08-19"/><occupation xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">poet</occupation><note xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="editorial"><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Born into a farming family, Bloomfield was too diminutive to make a success of this life. He moved to London in 1781 where he educated himself while learning 
    his trade as a cobbler. He also 
  attended the lecture of <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="FAW01">Joseph Fawcett</persName> (one of Godwin's principal 'oral instructors') in the Old Jewry. In 1798 
    <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="LOF01">Capel Lofft</persName> engineeered the publication 
